dataIdInfo.idAbs: This raster dataset represents the SCENARIO D analysis results of our evaluation of mechanical treatment opportunities in Sierra Nevada National Forests and the implications of restoring fire. We used a hierarchy of constraints that affect mechanical operability on Forest Service land to develop four scenarios of operational constraints (A-D). These scenarios capture the range of feasible interpretations of current standards and guides. Scenario D accesses all forest (regardless of timber value) on <35% slope within 2000’ of existing roads and all forest on 35-50% slope within 1000’ of existing roads. As a conservative approach, in some of our subsequent analyses we used scenario C to evaluate the effects of less restrictive mechanical constraints on fuel treatment implementation.

dataIdInfo.idPurp: Current rates of fuels treatment on western public lands are far below what is needed to effectively influence landscape-level fire behavior or approximate historic levels of annual area burned. In densely populated areas such as California, mechanically thinning is sometimes viewed as the only realistic means of increasing the pace and scale of fuels reduction treatment. However, mechanical treatments have their own constraints as well. Our analysis evaluated these constraints for National Forests in the Sierra Nevada bioregion. Given that the Forest Service recently adopted a new planning rule that initiates the development of new forest plans for most of the 155 National Forests and that three of the 'early adopters' forests for plan development (the Sierra, Sequoia and Inyo) are in the bioregion, the Sierra Nevada may be at the forefront for evaluating how these constraints affect forest planning.

report.measDesc: To determine which areas were constrained, we used a hierarchy of constraints, considering factors such as legislative restrictions, operational limitations and administrative constraints. This hierarchy is described in the lineage portion of this hierachy and was developed using best available scientific information: current standards and guidelines, feedback from practicing silviculturists, and corporate USDA Forest Service GIS databases.

Our analysis included the Lake Tahoe Basin Management Unit and nine of the eleven national forests examined in the 2013 USFS Sierra Nevada Bio-Regional Assessment (SNBA). We excluded the Klamath and Shasta-Trinity National Forests because although each has area within the SNBA, they are relatively small areas in the foothills that exclude more mountainous terrain affecting constraint patterns on the other ten National Forests. We anticipate our analysis could extend to other National Forests within the Pacific Southwest Region, and note that the parameters of the constraints could be further adjusted to increase applicability, according to professional local knowledge from both Forests already included in this analysis and also from Forests not yet analyzed. Although it is an important sensitive species in the Sierra Nevada, we did not include the fisher (Martes pennanti) in our analysis because there were no data identifying resting and core activity areas. If their habitat had been included, it would decrease the area available for mechanical treatment, but only on the Sierra and Sequoia National Forests where a small (<200 individuals) isolated population of fisher is present (Zielinski et al. 2005). Additional resources (such as fisher) could be included if suitable data is determined to be available and resource knowledge can provide appropriate methods for interpreting and applying mechanical constraints for a new resource. Note that in this analysis, we use the term mechanical treatment to refer to machine based fuels reduction and tree harvest (i.e., use of ground-based heavy equipment such as fellerbunchers and skidders). We did not include hand thinning with chainsaws within our scope of mechanical treatments because costs, speed, and fuel reduction effectiveness limit its use in the Sierra Nevada.

dataLineage.statement: We evaluated four basic categories of constraints on Forest Service land in a hierarchal order: biological conditions (L0), legislative restrictions (L1), operational limitations (L2) and administrative constraints (L3). We started with fixed limitations (L0) and gradually moved down to constraints with more flexibility in interpretation and implementation (L3). The constraints from each level are described in the process step below. Each Forest was processed independently, then all Forests were combined for the purposes of this dataset.

prcStep.stepDesc: Level 0 (L0) -- Biological. After starting with the total acres in each National Forest, we removed land identified as non-forest (i.e., rock, water, barren, meadow, shrub) and with a forest cover <10%.

Level 1 (L1) -- Legal. Considering only the productive forestland from L0, we removed areas where mechanical equipment is not allowed. Specifically, we removed USFS wilderness areas, USFS recommended wilderness areas, and inventoried roadless areas. Note that inventoried roadless areas where new road construction is allowed was not regarded as a constraint.

Level 2 (L2) -- Operational. We decided to develop four scenarios of operational constraints (A-D) to better capture the range of feasible interpretations of current standards and guides. Silviculturists gave us a range of operational constraints that were affected by three factors: slope, distance from existing road, and commercial value of the accessed forest. We used the California Wildlife Habitat Relationship system (CWHR) as an indirect measure of economic potential. We considered forests as having economic potentional if they were conifer forest types found in lower to mid-elevations, with an average tree diameter >= 11-24” and canopy cover >= 40%. Scenario A reflects the most strict adherence to current standards and guides where mechanical operations occur on <35% slopes and within 1000’ of existing roads. Scenario B extends the road building distance to 2000’ if more valuable timber is accessed to help defray costs. Scenario C adds working on steeper slopes (35-50%) within 500’ of existing roads if more valuable timber is accessed. Scenario D accesses all forest (regardless of timber value) on <35% slope within 2000’ of existing roads and all forest on 35-50% slope within 1000’ of existing roads. A reference table clarifying differences between scenarios is available by contacting the USDA Forest Service Pacific Southwest Regional Office (see contact information in this metadata).

Level 3 (L3) -- Administrative. We included the special administrative designations that are most common in the Sierra Nevada: riparian zones, California spotted owl (Strix occidentalis occidentalis) activity centers, northern goshawk (Accipiter gentilis) activity centers, and Research Natural Areas. Mechanical treatments are not strictly prohibited in these areas but they are highly restricted, and in practice are areas that are often left untreated. We used 100’-radius buffers for perennial streams and 50’-radius buffers for intermittent streams, following current standards and guidelines. In areas designated as wildland urban interface (WUI), treatment restrictions for sensitive species habitat apply to a 500’ radius around nest or activity center areas. In all other areas, it is 300 and 200 ac for spotted owls and goshawks around the nest/activity center, respectively.
